\f1 \cb3  May 16, 1830.\
\

\f0 \cb3 \uc0\u55356 \u56812 \u55356 \u56807 
\f1 \cb3  On this day, 
\f2\b \cb3 \'a0 Baron Jean-Baptiste-Joseph Fourier (1768-1830) died.
\f1\b0 \cb3  He was a French mathematician, Egyptologist and administrator who {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Mathematicians/Fourier.html"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 exerted}} strong influence on mathematical physics through his {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www-fourier.ujf-grenoble.fr/chaleur.html"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3\i \cb3 Th\'e9orie analytique de la chaleur}} (1822; 
\f3\i \cb3 The Analytical Theory of Heat
\f1\i0 \cb3 ). He introduced an infinite mathematical series to aid in solving conduction equations. This analysis technique allows the function of any variable to be expanded into a series of sines of multiples of the variable, which is now known as the Fourier series. His {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://micro.magnet.fsu.edu/optics/timeline/people/fourier.html"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 equations}} spawned many new areas of study in mathematics and physics, including the branch of optics named for him, have subsequently been applied other natural phenomena such as tides, weather and sunspots.\
\

